textDisplay:
I just made this recipe with one pack of tofu; after it had baked I kept half of it in a bowl, and set it aside to eat just as it is.
The other half, I sautéed some thinly sliced onions and crushed garlic, then added chunks of onions, red and green bell peppers, carrots, a piece of hot pepper, and salt; poured about half cup of water and two tablespoons of oyster sauce; stir and let it cooked, when almost done, then add the baked tofu and finished cooking.
I'm going to have my lunch which consists of coconut rice, a fresh green salad and the delicious tofu I just made; I've already tasted it and it's very delicious!
Thank you and God bless.

textDisplay:
Ross Q So, I haven’t really done a research on this much but I see some people have the same opinion as yours on the internet here and there. What’s the problem with soy products? I am simply curious and hoping you can share what you know!
In Japan, Korea and China, people eat tofu on daily basis. Those countries have one of the longest longevity in the world. When people say to avoid soy products, I am just confused. As long as it’s non GMO, shouldn’t they be healthy? Even with phytoestrogens, will there be enough phytoestrogens in tofu to be harmful to our bodies when consumed in normal serving size?
textOriginal:
